Judges propose to protect from the chairmen
The Presidential Council on Human Rights (HRC) on behalf of Vladimir Putin has developed proposals to strengthen the independence of the judiciary.
The ECHR proposes to limit the powers of court chairmen and to introduce their electability.
For the courts of appeal and cassation instances, the ECHR wants to introduce special districts that will not be tied to administrative-territorial division of the Russian Federation.
The Supreme Court should also submit its proposals within the framework of the presidential order.
The HRC has finalized proposals that will strengthen the independence of Russian justice.
This work was carried out on behalf of Vladimir Putin on 3 January 2017, which the President gave after meeting with members of the Council.
At a meeting with members of the Council of 8 December 2016 was discussed including individual cases judicial arbitrariness, as well as problems of public control in places of detention of citizens (see "Kommersant" 9 December).
The results of the work of the HRC were 25 proposals, which concern both the issues of ensuring the independence of judges and the detection of judicial errors, as well as the financing of courts and legal education.
One of the ideas of the Kremlin human rights defenders is to limit the powers of court chairmen to increase the independence of the rest of the judges.
If the candidate for the position of judge has successfully passed the contest and received the support of the judicial community, the chairman of the court, in the opinion of the ECHR, should submit it to the appointment, not having the right to refuse, as the law allows now.
It is also proposed to deprive the chairman of the right to distribute cases to the judges.
To do this, allow experts, can specially written computer program.
Also, the ECHR considers that the chairman does not have the right to "prejudge the results of the qualification certification of the judge, initiate his involvement in disciplinary responsibility, make decisions on establishing additional material payments."
At the same time, the presidential council considers it necessary to proceed to "of the judges of the court chairmen by the judges themselves" and "to give their powers for a relatively short period of time with mandatory rotation."
Now all chairmen of courts (from republican to district) are appointed for six years by the president upon proposal of the chairman of the Supreme Court of of the Russian Federation.
In order to protect the judges from the pressure of regional administrations, the HRC proposes to organize an appeal and cassation in the courts of general jurisdiction.
Now their structure is tied to the administrative no-territorial division of the Russian Federation.
The ECHR says that "it is necessary to ensure the organization of separate courts of appeal and cassation instances not at the level of regional judicial bodies in the subjects of the Russian Federation, but in the judicial districts."
Experts take as a basis for the practice of arbitration courts.
There are "judicial districts" that do not coincide with the administrative division in the Russian Federation, but they guarantee greater independence from regional officials, who are hampered by the use of "telephone law."
The HRC proposes to strengthen the judges of the world in order to consider some "categories of civil and administrative cases."
For example, the deprivation of parental rights, restoration at work, the protection of honor and dignity, the removal of driver's licenses, etc.
"These are just our proposals," - explained "Kommersant" the member of the ECHR, the judge of the Constitutional Court retired Tamara Morshchakova.
She also recalled that the President's instructions related not only to the, but also to the Supreme Court (SC), which has not yet disclosed its proposals.
The time for the of orders from the Armed Forces (among the co-executors - the Prosecutor General's Office and the Commissioner for Human Rights in the Russian Federation) still exists.
To report to Vladimir Putin about how effectively in ensuring the independence of justice is, the chairman of the Russian Federation Armed Forces Vyacheslav Lebedev must until September 1.
