"By her actions she killed Konrad Roy," - said the prosecutor.
"She interrupted his life to improve his own.
She did not recognize responsibility, "she said.
"She did not show remorse."
But lawyer Carter stated that it was "a tragic case, which she deeply regrets."
However, Judge Lawrence Monis said that, in his opinion, her "age, maturity level or even mental illness did not affect her actions."
The Prosecutor read out the statements of the mother Roy Lynn Roy, which says: "day has passed when I would not mourn the loss of my beloved son.
I want him to be proud of me and how I cope - I try to support his sisters, despite all the pain that will stay with us forever, "he says.
Roy Camdin Roy's sister said she was unfailed by the idea that she would never be able to attend his wedding or become his children's aunt.
"A person who has been with me always since my birth is a pain that will stay with me until the end of life," she said.
This case appears to be a legal precedent, because Massachusetts does not have a law that would mandate a person to commit suicide.
In 2014, when Roy found himself dead with symptoms of carbon monoxide poisoning, Carter was 17 years old.
The case attracted the attention of the entire country when it became known that he had been pushed to suicide by Carter's message.
"You can hang up, jump from the roof, kill yourself with a knife I don't know there are many ways," she wrote in several messages sent two weeks before his death, when he was resting with his family.
A few minutes before the suicide she wrote: "You have to do it, Conrad" and "You only have to the ignition, and you will become free and happy."
Judge Monis said that Carter wanted to get attention with the death of Roy, and forbade her to communicate with the media, not to give it to the desired.
The lawyers' opinions were divided.
One of the few who defended Carter was Amanda Knox, who was convicted in 2007 for the murder in Italy of his British neighbor's apartment and acquitted two years later.
The 30-year old Nox published in the "Los-Angeles Times special opinion, in which it was claimed:" Michelle Carter deserves sympathy and assistance, not prison. "
