Climate change threatens Lavender in Provence.
It has become a symbol of Provence and Southern France, but there are now fears that it is being threatened by climate change.
Lavender has grown worse due to dry weather and insect-borne diseases; this has a constant headache for scientists and farmers who are trying to find a solution.
Eric Shes, an expert from Provence agricultural research institute CRIEPPAM, says: "Lavender in Provence really is under threat, because in recent years this plant feels the effects of climate change: in the spring and especially in the autumn rains have become much less.
This affects the life of the lavender.
And still there are small cycades, jump on leaves insects carrying micro-bacteria; in very dry weather they become very much. "
There is a lot at stake.
Lavender not only attracts holidaymakers; lavender oil is very popular in and cosmetology.
Eric Shes says: "instead of very long ears with a large number of large flowers we have small, underdeveloped, weakened or generally absent.
So we have fewer parts containing essential oil. "
The decisions now being considered include improving water distribution and slowing evaporation from the soil, as well as spraying plants with protective mixture of clay and water and producing varieties more resistant to drought.
